deck_excerpt: DAD's home, and he brought snakes!
deck_description:
Ananta is a card that the moment I saw, I had to brew some kind of deck around it. Ultimately, the goals of this deck are quite simple, domino effect into getting a combination of Dark Armed Dragon and Ananta/Vaskii utilizing some straightforward combo lines. Until you get a hand that can do that (which can be turn 1 a surprising amount of the time), utilize the big booty of Reptilianne Gardna and the multiple sources of stubborn interaction this deck gains access to in order to control your opponent's ability to fight back. Also, be aware that the destruction effect on Ananta is not optional, so make sure that you have a second card you're okay with popping on the field if you set her up on turn 1 or if your opponent's board is clear.

The sideboard is mainly put together for your Zombie matchup, as Zombie World can be a nightmare to deal with as it completely shuts off Ananta. Fortunately, you do have main deck outs to the pesky Field Spell, as Vaskii only cares about the stats of what you tribute (which Dandylion sent off of Snake Rain/D.D.R. achieves quite nicely), and due to the lack of spells/traps that stick around on your side you can run a bevy of main deck backrow hate (Fun Tip: You can trigger your own Starlight Road using Heavy Storm if you wanna slam a Stardust Dragon on the field out of nowhere!). The D.D. monsters help with things like early Mezukis and Pyramid Turtles, and Nobleman just makes any defensive deck a minimal issue.

Any tips on how to improve this deck are greatly appreciated, thanks!

deck_excerpt: SPAM COUNTER TRAP HANDTRAP LIKE NO TOMORROW!!!
deck_description:
Galaxy-Eyes Tachyon's incredible new support has come out in the TCG with Maze of the Masters and in Masterduel with Ultimate Sparkle, so I thought I would come up with a article on our favourite space-borne dragons! The new support for the strategy enables 1-card combos with Schwarzchild Infinity Dragon which is effectively full combo since it enables a summon of a rank 8 monster (with a XYZ dragon lock) without using up your normal summon! This card is effectively at 12 copies in the deck with maxxed out copies of Seyfert, Seventh Ascension, and the new Schwarzchild Infinity and Seventh Tachyon cards! Not only that, the generic rank 8 "Divine Golden Shadow Dragon Dragluxion" adds any Tachyon or Galaxy card from deck on-summon! This enables Galaxy-Eyes Tachyon to pack 18 non-engine slots (21 if you include the Horus cards) making it capable of going 1st or second in Masterduel's cutthroat competitive ladder with handtraps/defensive staples! 
 
This insane consistency boost allows Galaxy-Eyes Tachyon to play to it's strengths, spamming its unique and insanely powerful countertrap "Tachyon Transmigration" and wielding ridiculously high attack stats (for ex. Draglubion with 17000ATK!)

 
Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!
 
ARCHETYPES AND DECKBUILDING
 
Galaxy-Eyes Tachyon is composed of 3 archetypes which all lead to basically the same endboard. The deck is also consistent enough to maindeck 18 staples! 

The GALAXY-EYES TACHYON is composed of 23 cards. While it is two archetypes, they basically mesh together to form a singular cohesive strategy. The Galaxy-Eyes Tachyon deck core is composed of x3 Seyfert (deck's main normal summon), x2 Tachyon Cloudragon (the "poplar" of the deck), x1 Spiral Galaxy Dragon, x2 Dark End Evaporation Dragon, x3 Galaxy-Eyes Tachyon Primal, x3 Schwarzschild Infinity Dragon (the main 1-card starter), x3 Seventh Ascension, x3 Seventh Tachyon and x3 Tachyon Transmigration. 
 
BYSTIAL cards count as handtraps and extenders for the strategy, and it also serves as good handtrap bait and breaks boards fairly easily since they're big beatsticks. It is composed of x1 Lubellion, x1 Magnamhut and x1 Druiswurm. 
 
This decklist has 15 STAPLE cards, thanks to the consistency upgrades the new Galaxy-Eyes Tachyon support cards offer. The handtraps amount to 12 in this deck and they are x3 Ash Blossom, x2 Imperm, x1 Nibiru, x1 Droll, x2 Maxx "C", and x3 Fuwalos. The last three staples are defensive cards, which are x2 Called By and x1 Crossout.
 
I chose to run maximum copies of Galaxy-Eyes Tachyon Primal rather than the usual 1-2 copies since it searches for Tachyon Transmigration, this deck's win condition. It's summon effect is a quick effect, so it can be used during your opponent's turn so you can play through Maxx C and Fuwalos! Not only that, it's an extender, so it's perfect for playing through interruption. The deck is 42 cards, so there is less chance of drawing into garnets like Galactic Spiral Dragon and Cloudragon.
 
COMBOS AND GAMEPLAN
 
Galaxy-Eyes Tachyon has a relatively simple and straightforward gameplan - get two level 8 monsters in the field, then summon XYZ summon the new support Divine Golden Shadow Dragon Dragluxion to further your plays. The endboard generally ends on Hope Harbinger's spell negate and the infamous ace-card of Tachyon Transmigration in-hand! If there are extenders, then the endboard may even have additional interaction like Photon Galaxy Lord's monster negate. 
 
Here is the standard 1-card opening combo for Galaxy-Eyes Tachyon: 
 
Schwarzschild Infinity Dragon = Tachyon Transmigration in-hand (Countertrap handtrap omni-negate) and Number 38: Hope Harbinger (spell negate). 
  1. Activate Schwarzschild Infinity Dragon and summon itself and Spiral Galaxy Dragon from deck.
  2. XYZ summon Divine Golden Shadow Dragon Dragluxion. 
  3. On-summon, Dragluxion searches for Tachyon Cloudragon.
  4. Cloudragon activates its effect to summon itself from hand when added from deck to hand.
  5. Activate Dragluxion's effect detaching two materials to summon Number 107: Galaxy-Eyes Tachyon Dragon from Extra deck and attach Galaxy Satellite Dragon to it.
  6. Tribute Cloudragon to summon Galaxy-Eyes Tachyon Primal from deck.
  7. On-summon, Primal adds from deck Tachyon Transmigration.
  8. Summon Spiral Galaxy Dragon from the GY.
  9. XYZ summon Draglubion using Primal and Spiral Galaxy.
  10. Activate Draglubion's effect detaching Spiral Galaxy Dragon to summon Number 38: Hope Harbinger Dragon Titanic Galaxy.

    If you have extenders, you can search for additional copies of Tachyon Transmigration for more omni-negates since it isn't once per turn! This deck also has a lot of gas, so it can power through interruption. Remember, two level 8s = full combo since you can summon Dragluxion!
Going second, you can summon Numeron Dragon and ONE SHOT KILL 17000ATK! Here is the basic combo:
 
Two level 8s = 17000ATK OTK! 
  1. XYZ summon Divine Golden Shadow Dragon Dragluxion using two level 8 monsters. 
  2. On-summon, Dragluxion searches for Tachyon Cloudragon.
  3. Cloudragon activates its effect to summon itself from hand when added from deck to hand.
  4. Activate Dragluxion's effect detaching two materials to summon Number 107: Galaxy-Eyes Tachyon Dragon from Extra deck and attach Galaxy Satellite Dragon to it.
  5. Tribute Cloudragon to summon Galaxy-Eyes Tachyon Primal from deck.
  6. On-summon, Primal adds from deck Tachyon Transmigration.
  7. Summon Spiral Galaxy Dragon from the GY.
  8. XYZ summon Draglubion using Primal and Spiral Galaxy.
  9. Activate Draglubion's effect detaching Spiral Galaxy Dragon to summon Numeron Dragon.
  10. Detach 1 material from Numeron Dragon to make it 17000 ATK. 
If your opponent was silly enough to leave even a 8000ATK monster on the field in attack position, you'd STILL OTK through it!
 
GENERAL TIPS
  • Remember the various "locks" when playing with this deck! Schwarzchild Infinity Dragon locks you into Dragon XYZ monsters for the entire turn. Number 97: Draglubion locks special summoning for the rest of the turn after it's effect is used.
  • I chose to run maximum copies of Galaxy-Eyes Tachyon Primal rather than the usual 1-2 copies since it searches for Tachyon Transmigration, this deck's win condition. It's summon effect is a quick effect, so it can be used during your opponent's turn so you can play through Maxx C and Fuwalos! Not only that, it's an extender, so it's perfect for playing through interruption.
  • If you enter your battle phase with a Galaxy-Eyes Tachyon Dragon with Galaxy Satellite Dragon as one of it's materials, detach it, so you can boost your attack to 10700ATK!
  • When Khaos Starsource Dragon is banished, especially with Dark End Evaporation Dragon's effect, it can make your level 4 Dragon on the field level 8. Do this play when you have Seyfert or Cloudragon (both level 4s) on the field so you can go for rank 8 plays!
  • Seventh Ascension, Seventh Tachyon, Bystial Lubellion and Seyfert are excellent handtrap baits, especially if you have full combo (2 level 8s) already in-hand.
  • When you're destroying face-up cards on the field, you can overlay on top of any Galaxy-Eyes you control Galaxy-Eyes Full Armor Photon Dragon to destroy 1 card. Then overlay again on top of Full Armor Photon Dragon Cipher Blade Dragon for another destruction!
Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!
 
CONCLUDING REMARKS
 
Kite and Mizar's Galaxy-Eyes cards certainly received a massive glow-up with their new support from Ultimate Sparkle and Maze of the Masters - but the question is, will it succeed in Masterduel ladder?
 
GLHF Duelists!

deck_excerpt: Negate my effects or pop my backrow.  I dare ya
deck_description:
Kurikara works similairly to Kaijus as a DM, and i wanted to take advantage of the differences.

Theme: Punishing the opponent for playing the game

- One half of the deck focuses heavily on strong backrow cards that clear boards and deal heavy amounts of burn damage.  This hopefully incentivises the opponent to blindly pop your backrow and play into the second half of the deck

- The other half of the deck are cards that activate when destroyed by an opponents card effect.  As many relevant Waking the Dragon type effects that i can find and fit.  

- The third and smallest half of the deck is a mix of stall cards like the timelords, and draw power because this deck tends to lose card advantage veeerrrrryyyyy quickly and needs time to recuperate.
A mistake Syrus would be proud of

deck_excerpt: Pure Apophis Midrange, with a Dragon Ravine splash for resiliency and extension
deck_description:
There's a lot of buzz around the Apophis (Odion) cards, especially around possible supplemental engines to help you combo and break boards. I've heard most people talk about the Kashtira engine as the best option for a true one-card combo by going into Arsenal Falcon, making Romulus, and dumping Destrudo with Zephyros in rotation to make AFD and get into the new field spell. I think this avenue fails for a number of reasons, but most importantly:

 

1. It uses your normal summon anyway for Kashtira Riseheart, so you are unable to use Man with the Mark as a starter if you go for the Fenrir 1-card combo.

 

2. If you get interrupted on your Arsenal Falcon, or your Romulus, or even your Fenrir, you're SOL. If you don't have Called By/Crossout and they negate your Falcon, you have no follow-up beyond hard drawing Treasures of the Kings--which, if you did that, why are we bothering with the convoluted Kashtira combo anyway?

 

Obviously using Fenrir as a starter allows you to have a true 1-card combo--the material you start with gives you a line into Silhouhatte Rabbit without needing anything else in hand other than a discard to Ravine, but the inherent fragility and non-extensibility of this line makes me shy away from it.

 

However, by using a small Dragon Ravine package as a supplemental engine, we can achieve largely the same effect while also providing some much needed flexibility and resiliency to the main combo. Man with the Mark remains our primary starter, with Anubis and Small World as a way to search out. Iff they negate the Man with the Mark, and you have any of the five ways to get to Dragon Ravine (3x Remus, 2x Ravine), you can use Ravine to dump Destrudo and go into AFD using the Man with the Mark. This gameplan DOES still require you to have an extra card to set to trigger the Treasures of the Kings, but that can be solved with some clever deckbuilding to make sure you have enough settable cards to fulfill this requirement while maintaining a good core engine and non-engine base.

 

In addition, having so much access to Dragon Ravine means, even without Man with the Mark, starting with Ravine and any non-Tuner normal summon means you can go into AFD and Apophis combo WITHOUT using Man with the Mark. This line is obviously more fragile--but it also means more hands are playable, even with a solid number of hand traps. Because of this, we need our hand traps to be non-Tuners--which means no ghost girls or Effect Veiler. We also need our hand traps to be ultra-impactful. This deck has a hard time going second, so we need our non-engine to be solid board breakers or game-ending hand traps. For that reason, we're playing Fuwalos, Droll, and Nibiru. In order to maintain a high number of Spells/Traps to set alongside our Treasures of the Kings, we're playing Impermanence and Book of Eclipse, as we need these to be useful going second but also fine to set on our own.

 

The Book of Eclipse slot could also be used for Forbidden Droplet instead. However, I default to Book for a few reasons:

 

1. We're already so card hungry with Dragon Ravine as an extender and Small World as a searcher, that it can be difficult to even have enough material for Droplet to good work into an established board.

 

2. Book of Eclipse can actually be used as an insulator against targeted negation when attempting to resolve Man with the Mark or AFD--which is a resiliency we sorely need.

 

3. Book of Eclipse has synergy with the Trap Monster line-up. Pumping out our Trap Monsters to interrupt the opponent first and then following up with Book of Eclipse actually resets the Trap Monsters (as they have the text "It's still a Trap") to be used later. This is obviously win-more, but it means that, in an intense grind-game, it is not as much of a liability as it might otherwise be.

 

Finally, the addition of Dragunity Remus and the sculpting of our hand trap lineup means Small World can bridge any of our handtraps into either Dragon Ravine (through Droll->Mulcharmy->Remus or Mulcharmy->Droll->Remus) or an Apophis Starter (Droll->Anubis->Man, Mulcharmy/Remus -> Droll -> Anubis, Nibiru -> Anubis -> Man) or even Serket if Treasures search is Ashed (Droll/Nibiru/Mulcharmy -> Anubis/Man -> Serket). That means, even though it takes a card, we can flex our non-engine lineup into starters or extenders as needed.

 

The Apophis typical endboard is the following:

 

1. Silhouhatte Rabbit

 

2. Divine Spirit of Apophis

 

3. Statue of Anguish Pattern

 

4. Apophis the Serpent

 

5. 2x Apophis the Swamp Deity

 

 

 

This is around 5-6 pops and two mass omni-negates on the field. This is a suite of endboard interaction that is particularly potent in a format that relies on monsters either on the field or in banishment. Spot removal is at a premium, and this deck ends on basically all spot removal. This can be a problem against decks like Fire King that prefer to be destroyed, but it is possible to play around their destructions.

 

All in all, I'm very, very happy with list, and I invite you to try it out!

deck_description:
Unstoppable. Untamable. Unextinct.
This is a beginner-friendly Domain Format list built upon a $11.99 MSRP purchase of the Structure Deck: Dinosmasher's Fury. It consists of a $10 upgrade of cards purchased from sites like TCGplayer. (It is unlikely you will find this deck at MSRP any longer because it came out 7 years ago)

Deckmaster: Evoltile Megachirella 
Domain Restriction: FIRE // REPTILE // DINOSAUR // DRAGON 

List based on my https://ygoprodeck.com/deck/serpentine-sovereignty-464985, editted to have a larger focus on Dinosaurs with a measure for budget. 

To create this upgrade, please remove these 15 cards and any duplicate cards from the SD: Dinosmasher's Fury (reference the sidedeck): 
Note: 2 cards of the included 41-card structure deck will be duplicates

  • ydke://gIbgBIwCIQEghvIA6hp9Ak1PuwBvz/EF65JMApOApAK/EfYEUku8AhT1JQIfq/EE+TLFAGzkBgFBIdICWXtjBAvqDQC5U+sCI9adAoD9GAAP6rMFk17HAeElbwL7u6gC!!o3iPAgUpeQMnOWwBD4MWAXkSDgXT8RgFMKAIA9HrPQDXQsUDEoJoAGDEDwAcHRMF6c1wAASPUwXqoDgC!
  • View on YGOprodeck
  • Structure Deck Full Contents (YGOprodeck)

Next, you will want to buy and add these 52 cards to the deck: 

  • ydke://orLXBYqA5wBjCTwDFhYEAQGuagTkTFkAei5lAGIkJQH3yPoBvadvAZqqBwNw/cgEfY19Auw6sgTCz8UCz2DjBUfltwOkObgDQPO7BQcbRwSdFnAFtxvpBEMlkAV8toYDiVcRAg31DAHghQcCf7PcAYe+bQExkUYC47AqA3jXfQX7bU0CPJusBPkQWAS7+qgA!3T/vA41YjALvdhoBalshAZONUwJsWNMDvbMWALvJfQSS+pQA08DYAitSnAVgtwkEmf+HBQch6QLF5yMF!ExLHAA==!
  • View on YGOprodeck
  • View on TCGplayer Cart

Additional Resources can be found here:
https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1c8_W7TLHoExz9Iq2yNBKG4kniKN3fjamfMVRehPRitQ/edit?usp=sharing

Domain Format General Rules:

  • Singleton Format: Every card restricted to 1 copy per deck.
  • 60-card Format: Each Main Deck must contain exactly 60 cards.
  • 4-player Pods: Each player competes individually in an all-out battle against three opponents.
  • Deckmaster Restrictions: Each player chooses a "Deckmaster" which dictates the allowed types and attributes for their deck.
  • Deckmaster Contract: A Deckmaster can be summoned from a designated "Deckmaster Zone" using normal summoning rules. After switching zones, Deckmasters may return to the "Deckmaster Zone," where they start the game.

Refer here for additional rules and exceptions:

https://www.domainformat.com/rules 

Broad Categories

This simple strategy has cards that fall into three simple categories:

  • Dino Beatdown
  • Recursion
  • Card Access

Reccommended Combo Guide:
Turn 1: 
https://www.duelingbook.com/replay?id=1038951-69226388

Turn 2:
https://www.duelingbook.com/replay?id=1038951-69271471

What do we want our Deckmaster to do? 

- Turn 1 combo
- Refill XYZ materials
- Provide Ability to discard
- Access Dinosaur Engine ( Xeno Meteorus )
- Provide Spell/Trap destruction on demand ( Evolsaur Diplo )

Our deckmaster is surprisingly more versitile than they seem at first read. The ability to not only start our plays but continue to be extremely valuable throughout the entire game accumulates an unmatched advantage over decks with simple deckmasters. 

An underrated part of the deckmaster is access to Evolsaur Diplo, who destroys spells and traps on summon. Use this to destroy problematic floodgates or advantage generators. In addition, we regain this ablity once Evolsaur Diplo is shuffled back into deck by our recursion pieces.
Another target is Evolsaur Vulcano, which can immediatly resummon an evolsaur in our GY to make the Rank-4 Evolzar Dolkka.
Lastly, to synergize with the Dinosaur package, Evoltile Megachirella can summon Xeno Meteorus, destroying a monster summoned by Miscellaneousaurus and accessing synchro plays through that. 
  
The refill of XYZ material allows us to revive powerful XYZ monsters from the grave without losing access to their effects.
Many of our cards, like Aleirtt, the Ogdoadic Dark  only have effects in GY, so Evoltile Megachirella's discard cost to activate its effects happens to be beneficial. 

In a deck like this, a deckmaster like Evoltile Megachirella provides extremely valuable consistency and deck functionality.

The Recursion

- Resummon Ogdoadics
- Return Miscellaneousaurus to the GY using Aleirtt, the Ogdoadic Dark 
- Revive XYZ and Refill XYZ materials ( Evoltile Megachirella + Nephilabyss, the Ogdoadic Overlord )
- I.A.S. -Invasive Alien Species- , Dark Hole Dragon , Transcendosaurus Meteorus , Ragnaraika Selene Snapper 

This aspect here is the core of the deck. Every time we resummon Nauya, the Ogdoadic Remnant by Keurse, the Ogdoadic Light , we can add an Ogododic Spell or Trap. Aleirtt, the Ogdoadic Dark and Keurse, the Ogdoadic Light are both able to activate effects to special summon themselves from the GY.

Each time we resummon Aleirtt, the Ogdoadic Dark , we can another opportunity to use Miscellaneousaurus by returning it to GY from Banishment. Thus, we can summon yet another Dinosaur to the field every turn. 

I.A.S. -Invasive Alien Species- gets out of control very quickly with its ablity to resummon itself, destroy monsters, and increase its attack every turn. Given the plethera of powerful field spells people enjoy playing, this likely happens quite frequently.

Use Number 60: Dugares the Timeless and Nephilabyss, the Ogdoadic Overlord to revive Dragon XYZ from our GY, then refill their materials using the effect of Evoltile Megachirella.
Good Revival Targets: 

  • Galaxy-Eyes Cipher Dragon: Steals a monster
  • Galaxy Photon Dragon / Dinowrestler Pankratops: Pop a card
  • Ragnaraika Selene Snapper: Destroy 2 Spells/Traps 
  • Horned Saurus: Attack Directly
  • Archnemeses Eschatos: Boardwipe
  • Sauropod Brachion: Flip board facedown 
  • [Other Endboard Pieces/Negates/HighAtk]  

Our free summons will continue until time ends, and through that, we make sure we always end up ahead every turn rotation.

Dino Beatdown

- big monster (Transcendosaurus Glaciasaurus)
- Search Field Spells ( Horned Saurus )
- Pop/neutralize monsters ( Ultimate Conductor Tyranno )
- Attack modification ( Dinomorphia Rexterm )
- Lasting staying power 

Dinosaurs are the second aspect of evolution for reptiles, and as such are much stronger and scarier. Our cards like Ultimate Conductor Tyranno can neutralize boards, Dinowrestler Pankratops can remove threats, and Transcendosaurus Glaciasaurus becomes a pain for our opponents to remove. The fantastic aspect of this deck is its ability to access all of this through Misc!

As I’m sure you’ve noticed, we only have one Miscellaneousaurus. BUT we can access it multiple times using Aleirtt, the Ogdoadic Dark returning Miscellaneousaurus to GY! As we continue to use Miscellaneousaurus, we increase the arsenal of things it can access, and thus gets more powerful

The combos are here:

Using Misc for baby, then NS Deckmaster for Xeno:
[Banish 2]: Summon Petiteranodon who can be destroyed by Xeno Meteorus (who is summoned by our Deckmaster)

Using Misc for Extra Deck plays (after reshuffling key pieces of combo):
[Banish 4]: Summon Evolsaur Lios or Kaitoptera or Dinomorphia Therizia to summon Evolzar Solda  or Horned Saurus or Dinomorphia Rexterm respectivly.

Example Combo for Turn 2 return Miscellaneousaurus to GY:
https://www.duelingbook.com/replay?id=1038951-69271471

The endboard monsters:

- Ultimate Conductor Tyranno // Transcendosaurus Glaciasaurus 
- Dinomorphia Rexterm 
- Cosmic Slicer Zer'oll
- Evolzar Solda // Evolzar Dolkka 
- Galaxy-Eyes Cipher Dragon 

Strange Stand-alone cards

These cards may seem off at first glance. Here are their reasons for inclusion in this deck:

  • Polymerization 
    Searchable through Kaitoptera and summons Horned Saurus which searches Lair of Darkness

  • Soul Release along with Gigantic Thundercross 
    Targets down opposing recursion engines
  • Alien Stealthbuster, I.A.S. -Invasive Alien Species- 
    Searchable through Nauya, the Ogdoadic Remnant, and the plethora of reptile GY senders, in addition to "A" Cell Recombination Device and Mysterious Triangle 

  • Frostosaurus
    The garnet nessisary for Xeno Meteorus to summon Transcendosaurus Glaciasaurus
  • Pitknight Earlie
    Great card that is hard to fully remove from the field due to resummon when due by battle or card effect

Tips

  • You don't like your Ogdoadic recursion pieces getting banished from the GY, so chain a revival spell to the banish to deny that. As a bonus, you can still activate their effects on summon even if they aren't summoned by their own effect!

  • Horned Saurus can set a field spell from the GY as well as from Deck, so don't feel bad if you need to discard Lair of Darkness. Similarly, Kaitoptera can add Polymerization from GY, so Polymerization  can be discarded if need. 
  • Be careful not to overuse the deckmaster Evoltile Megachirella. Discard fodder and life points are both finite, and this deck does not have in-combo ways to efficiently generate more of either. There are a total of 4 targets you can reasonably summon using it.

  • Early access to Raika no Kurokamitsuki will ensure peace of mind against any continous spells/traps your opponent may attempt to keep around. This card can ensure consistant access to a spell/trap destruction effect by reviving itself from the GY. In a pinch, you can NS the deckmaster for fodder to activate its revival effect.

  • You will need to massively alter your combo lines if you draw Animadorned Archosaur. Perhaps try to access King of the Feral Imps to search Nauya, the Ogdoadic Remnant in that scenerio.  
    • If you draw Evolsaur Lios, Normal Summon Lios and proceed to combo normally. Since Evo-Singularity needs an "Evoltile" monster in GY to activate: at the end of the combo use Cosmic Slicer Zer'oll's to NS your Deckmaster.  
  • Between Lair of Darkness [ Horned Saurus ], and Dogoran, the Mad Flame Kaiju [ Souleating Oviraptor ], this deck has plenty of accessible ways to remove threats that cannot be destroyed by card effects or targetted.

  • Leaning on your varied recursion pieces to play an attrition gameplan should be the overall goal. The boards that this deck can make are not impressive on their own.  

To Recap: 

Important Cards: Miscellaneousaurus , Aleirtt, the Ogdoadic Dark , Ultimate Conductor Tyranno , Evolzar Dolkka 

Strategy Elevator Pitch: Keep summoning more and more Dinosaurs to brandish the might of the prehistoric!

Other considerations:
 Number 60: Dugares the Timeless, Galaxy Photon Dragon, Lavalval Chain, Planet Pollutant Virus, Bystial Magnamhut, Number 38: Hope Harbinger Dragon Titanic Galaxy, Promethean Princess, Bestower of Flames, Card of Safe Return, Reptilianne Ramifications, [Night Sword Serpent  ] , Number 107: Galaxy-Eyes Tachyon Dragon, Jewels of the Valiant , Circle of the Fire Kings , Gizmek Kaku, the Supreme Shining Sky Stag , Five-Headed Link Dragon , Salamangreat Almiraj , Reptilianne Vaskii , [Stardust Trail] , Lava Golem, Kurikara Divincarnate , Dinomorphia Rexterm , Salamangreat Sunlight Wolf , Ragnaraika Armored Lizard , [ Vanguard of the Underground Emperor  ] , Sacrifice Level-Up , Salamangreat Revive , Giant Rex , Supersoaring , Primite Howl , Xyz Revenge , Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring , Called by the Grave , Monster Reborn , Special Hurricane , Xyz Force , Soul Release , Book of Eclipse 

Before Time Had a Name, They Ruled the World.

NB: replace numbers protection with new and improved "XYZ Unbreakable Barrier" for the better Astraltopia search card. Dodododo Warrior with Dodododo Warrior (new), Goblindbergh with Gogogo Goblindbergh (new). Side deck in utopic future zexal also (new).

Strategic Summary:

Welcome back for the final CDP of the month, and this time we’re merging two Xyz themes into one cohesive strategy. First up is the Lyrilusc WIND Winged Beast theme, an archetype dedicated to R1NK Xyz Monsters and attaching a lot of material to Lyrilusc – Assembled Nightingale. Between Lyrilusc – Bird Call, Lyrilusc – Cobalt Sparrow, Lyrilusc – Celestine Wagtail, and Lyrilusc – Recital Starling, this theme has all of the consistency-boosters one could hope for, as you grab the specific pairings of monsters needed for combos. Beyond the OTK combo of a multi-direct-attacking Assembled for game, the Lyrilusc also have some neat tricks like the full-board monster negate of Lyrilusc – Bird Strike and the spinning of Lyrilusc – Ensemblue Robin. But where this theme shines is its ability to easily merge two Winged Beast Xyz monsters into one with Lyrilusc – Bird Sanctuary, empowering them to take on the world… or eat it, if you’re Epurrely Plump!

 

That brings us to our second theme, the Fairy Xyz archetype Purrely! The Purrely archetype uses two Level 1 monsters to faux-Xyz Summon out its R2NK Xyz Monsters, and once the R2NK amasses enough material, it can be upgraded to a R7NK boss. Do you see where I’m going with this yet? If not, the goal of this hybrid is to combine Lyrilusc Level 1s and leftover Purrely or Purrelyly from your Quick-Play Spell activations to make Lyrilusc Xyz Monsters, then transfer the Lyrilusc and its associated Xyz Material to a Purrely R2NK (after Reprodocus turns it to Winged Beast of course), giving you everything you need to make a R7NK Purrely boss. No strings attached, no hoops or multiple Quick-Play Spells needed. Besides, this also gives the deck the benefit of being able to run Harpie’s Feather Storm, giving your Expurrely Noir extra help in the control department going into their turn. Consume the power of the storm, with the Lyrilusc and Purrely themes!

deck_excerpt: Final Countdown Win ft. Royal Magical Library
deck_description:
Hey there! In this deck, we will win with "Final Countdown" using "Royal Magical Library". You heard me right, as I have done it previously in Panda-Tethys-Junk decks. So, it should be easy.

 

 

Gameplan

1) Draw your whole deck with Library. You can find it with "Seventh Tachyon" thanks to Number 104.

2) With Double Summon + Pendulum Summon + Trismagistus, make sure you have 3 x Level 4 monsters. Then, XYZ Summon Knight with these two and play Countdown + Barrier + Void.

3) Activate Knight to bring forth The World and choose the outcome as heads with Barrier to skip your opponent's turn at the cost of sending two of your monsters you control to GY. These will be remaining Level 4 monster and Knight.

4) With turn skipped via The World and Void sending your hand to the GY, you can summon Balerdroch + Cockroach forever for The World to skip turns until you win the duel with "Final Countdown".

deck_excerpt: Jackpot 7 FTK ft. Iron Chain Snake + Machina Fortress
deck_description:
Welcome! In this deck, we will win with "Jackpot 7" thanks to interaction between Snake and Fortress, with the help of Chalice. Let's get into action!

 

 

Gameplan

1) When you have sent Shamisen to GY and 3 x Jackpot 7 cards in your hand, Link Summon Saryuja but don't use Panda as material. Then, Special Summon Snake with Saryuja and Special Summon Fortress with its ability...

  • If your opponent went first and their side is full, use Coral/Wurm/Legatia to free up a space for Fortress later on.

2) Give Fortress to your opponent with "Shien's Spy" and play Chalice on Snake. Then, Special Summon Shamisen and Synchro Summon Smashtank with Panda + Shamisen.

3) Activate Smashtank to discard everything in your hand but 3 x Jackpot 7 cards. Next, use Snake to target on Fortress, which leads into your opponent discarding "Jackpot 7" by force via Fortress. Repeating it two more times lets you win with "Jackpot 7".

deck_excerpt: Angel of Mischief FTK ft. Grand Pileup
deck_description:
Hello and welcome to another deck guide, where I'll show you another means of victory with "Ghostrick Angel of Mischief". This time, "Goblin Biker" archetype will be utilized. Let's see how, shall we?

 

 

Gameplan

1) Discard The World + Oni with Ravenous and Synchro Summon Baronne with Ravenous + Tuner. Next, Link Summon Saryuja and Special Summon Kuriboh with it.  Then, Special Summon Chaos Emperor Dragon with its ability to unlock "Primal Seed" loop and activate "Light Barrier".

2) Revive the following monsters with "Monster Reborn" but make sure you have a space behind any Extra Monster Zone (EMZ) for Goblin Biker and do a cleanup with Offerings to have space for them:

  • Martial + Integrator = Goblin Biker
  • The World
  • Oni

3) When you have revived The World, choose the outcome as heads with "Light Barrier". Then, use Oni to reduce the Rank of Goblin Biker from 3 to 2. Now, you can Link Summon Reprodocus with Saryuja + Oni, right above Goblin Biker.

4) Revive Baronne and set "Grand Pileup" to pop it afterwards. This lets you use its ability from GY to feed Goblin Biker in addition to being able to fetch from BZ with "Primal Seed" loop. You will repeat this step until Goblin Biker has 9 materials but don't fetch "Grand Pileup" just yet.

5) Pop Baronne with Offerings to not deck-out. Next, revive Baronne with "Monster Reborn" to reset Baronne, which lets you repeat what was explained in #4.

6) If you have played "Into the Void" beforehand, you need to set the following cards to not discard them to GY by accident:

  • Primal Seed
  • Monster Reborn
  • Scroll of Bewitchment
  • Astral Force
  • Offerings to the Doomed

7) End your turn and use The World to send Baronne + Kuriboh to GY in order to skip your opponent's turn. When it's your turn, revive Kuriboh first to unlock "Primal Seed" loop again. Then, repeat this step in addition to what was explained in #4 and #5.

8) When Goblin Biker has 9 materials, use Scroll and Reprodocus to change Goblin Biker into DARK Fairy. It allows you to play Astral Force and overlay into Mischief to seal the game.

 

If you wonder how to save up some SR and UR points, I can show you:

- "Monster Reborn" can be found by completing the tutorial to save 30 UR!

- "Pot of Avarice" can be collected by purchasing "Re-Contract Universe" deck. 90 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

deck_description: Its 3 copies of the Blue-Eyes Whtie Destiny structure deck

The current Masterduel meta is a slogfest of unbreakable FTK boards, every deck has a bazillion handtraps/extenders, and everything is a "pile" deck of Fiendsmith, Azamina, Millenium, Snake-Eyes and White Forest. BOOOORING!
 
Unfortunately, the Duelist Cup for March 2025 reflects the worst the meta has to offer, so laddering up in the event for those sweet, sweet gems has become a frustrating experience for many. Want quick, easy gems from the Duelist Cup? I got the answer for you! That is... Sky Striker Tenpai!
 
While your opponent spends 10+ minutes building their board, get yourself a snack, wash some dishes, clean up your room, then come back to OBLITERATE their board with your power spells, Sky Striker arsenal, and their lifepoints with Tenpai Dragons! This is my personal deck that I've used to reach max Duelist Cup level in a mere 3ish hours. Hope you can do it too!

Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

GLHF Duelists!

Jackpot 7 FTK ft. Junk Speeder + Criosphinx
deck_description:
Greetings! This is a "Jackpot 7" deck, where "Criosphinx" will be utilized while playing as "Junk Speeder". Let's get into action!

 

 

Gameplan

1) Draw your whole deck and place Pendulum Monsters into their Zones. Make sure you have 1 x Level 1 dude in your hand.

2) Pendulum Summon Doom and Criosphinx. Then, give Criosphinx to the opponent with "Shien's Spy" but if opposing side is full, use Coral/Ravenous/Legatia to free up a space for Criosphinx.

3) Bring forth Level 1 dude and bounce it back to your hand with Birdman. Interaction between Doom and Birdman allows you to use the ability of Birdman as many times as you like.

4) Returning a monster to your hand triggers Criosphinx and you can discard all Jackpot 7 cards. Repeat what was explained in #3 until you win the duel via "Jackpot 7".

 

If you wonder how to save up some SR and UR points, I can show you:

- "Reinforcement of the Army" can be found by completing the tutorial to save 30 UR!

- "Flower Cardian Moonflowerviewing" can be found within "Hand of Fate" Secret Pack to save 30 SR!

- "Koa'ki Meiru Doom" can be found within "Iron Core Synthetics" Secret Pack to save 30 SR!

- "Genex Ally Birdman" can be found within "Elemental Exchanges" Secret Pack to save 30 SR!

- "Into the Void" can be either found within "Life Force Control System" or "The Infinite Void" Secret Packs to save 90 SR!

- "Doomking Balerdroch" can be found within "Abyssal Underworld" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

- "T.G. Hyper Librarian" can be found within "Futuristic Creatures" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

- "Junk Converter" + "Junk Speeder" can be found within "Scrap Iron Soldiers" Secret Pack to save 90 SR and 30 UR!

- "Jet Synchron" can be found within "Stardust Ties" Secret Pack to save 30 SR!

- "Junk Synchron" + "Ravenous" + "Jackpot 7" can be found within "Legacy Pack" to save 210 SR!

- These following cards can be found within "Evoked Dragon of Miracles" Secret Pack to save 270 SR and 60 UR:

  • 3 x Formula Synchron >>> 90 SR
  • 1 x Stardust Wurm >>> 30 SR
  • 1 x Stardust Synchron >>> 30 SR
  • 1 x Wheel Synchron >>> 30 SR

So, in total, you can save up to 780 SR and 180 UR, if you are willing to spend some gems. Other SR and UR cards I didn't mention are essential.

 

That's all for this one. If you have any questions, feel free to ask. Have fun in Master Duel!

Here are a few options for interesting deck descriptions, playing with different tones and angles: Option 1 (Focus on Ritual Chaos): "Witness the unholy symphony of fallen angels and ancient dragons! This deck weaves a tapestry of Ritual madness, where the celestial grace of the Voiceless Voice clashes with the infernal might of the Darklords. Saffira and Lucifer dance a macabre tango, fueled by Desires and fueled by the forbidden power of 'Contact.' Prepare for a whirlwind of banishing, summoning, and divine intervention that leaves your opponent questioning their very existence. Will you ascend with the light, or succumb to the darkness? The choice is... chaotic." Option 2 (Emphasizing the Darklord/Voiceless Voice Fusion): "They said light and darkness could never coexist. They were wrong. This deck is a testament to the beautiful, terrifying synergy between the angelic Voiceless Voice and the demonic Darklords. From the serene prayers of Saffira to the rebellious might of Morningstar, experience a ritual engine unlike any other. 'Contact' the forbidden, 'Pray' for salvation, and watch as your opponent's carefully laid plans crumble beneath the weight of combined celestial and infernal power. This isn't just a deck; it's a divine/demonic pact." Option 3 (A More Menacing/Dramatic Tone): "The whispers have begun. The Voiceless Voice, once a beacon of purity, now echoes with the chilling commands of the Darklords. This deck is a conduit to the abyss, a ritualistic descent into madness. 'Desires' will fuel our dark ambitions, 'Contact' will bind us to the shadows, and 'Rebellion' will shatter the heavens. Witness the rise of the First Darklord, empowered by the very light it seeks to extinguish. Prepare to be judged, and found wanting." Option 4 (Short and Punchy): "Angels and demons party. Ritual style. Light? Dark? We're taking both. Prepare for ritual chaos, banishing shenanigans, and a whole lot of 'Contact'!"

The lock of Trickstar Festival really breaks your neck and IT breaks my heart but Licorice isn't worth playing.

The toy engine searches Candina. 

I play Trickstar because it's my favorite. But pure it's really not good at all. With this change it has a little more potential and it's fun. 

Try it! If you have other ideas that could work pls comment. Thank you.

deck_name: $20 Structure Starter: Beware of Traptrix [Domain Format]]
deck_excerpt: Domain Format: Budget Structure Deck Tune-Ups
deck_description:
Temptation Leads to Capture.
This is a beginner-friendly Domain Format list built upon a $11.99 MSRP purchase of the Structure Deck: Beware of Traptrix. It consists of a $20 upgrade of cards purchased from sites like TCGplayer.
(I blame Ragnaraika the Evil Seed for eating HALF THE BUDGET)

Deckmaster: Beargram, Shelled Emperor of the Forest Crown 
Domain Restrictions: EARTH // INSECT // PLANT
Made for Domain Format: Join the Community Discord!

To create this upgrade, please remove these 11 cards and any duplicate cards from the SD: Beware of Traptrix (reference the sidedeck): 
Note: 2 cards of the included 48-card structure deck will be duplicates

  • ydke://YOkzAliXxQGSxE0DPua6AvXxeAVlfO4EWJPFAip/uAGixH4E4vc/BeorxwXMF+wC2VOuAajl5gIpV8MA+9wUAX32vwBgtugCuvo4AF6jwAFvdu8AoP8lBDdj4QHr5XwEzf3jBXQxQAC/9nEEIevDARNYDwA=!3cIZAIhchQMJWmMAUjrfAsuIDgC7pGME!Tn8RBeLRtQEylRIFCV85ARGO9wAYxBUE7cK3Ba8j3gA94VEFnOG9AAtCxgQ=! 
  • View on YGOprodeck
  • Structure Deck Full Contents (YGOprodeck)

Next, you will want to buy and add these 41 cards to the deck: 

  • ydke://txvpBCKSYwWtkX8B4xrMBSBdyAXz48gBZbAwAuUZlQFt9owAIhO0A7d8AgGb9OgFp99JABiBDQAoJiECWXtjBOqsnwQ96gcF5IZeA3+JYwRoXrEC4IUHAlozaQS0dU8CSp5aBTZXLQB4y18A5Or+A/O1OAScGeMAVBd0AA==!5qeOAF9MZgVsbDoAsJCFAhj3MwQNGpICCYBDATdJawSyL4UA!AQmeAQ==!
  • View on YGOprodeck
  • View on TCGplayer Cart

Additional Resources can be found here:
https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1c8_W7TLHoExz9Iq2yNBKG4kniKN3fjamfMVRehPRitQ/edit?usp=sharing

Domain Format General Rules:

  • Singleton Format: Every card restricted to 1 copy per deck.
  • 60-card Format: Each Main Deck must contain exactly 60 cards.
  • 4-player Pods: Each player competes individually in an all-out battle against three opponents.
  • Deckmaster Restrictions: Each player chooses a "Deckmaster" which dictates the allowed types and attributes for their deck.
  • Deckmaster Contract: A Deckmaster can be summoned from a designated "Deckmaster Zone" using normal summoning rules. After switching zones, Deckmasters may return to the "Deckmaster Zone," where they start the game.

Refer here for additional rules and exceptions:

https://www.domainformat.com/rules 

Broad Categories

This simple strategy has cards that fall into three simple categories:

  • Trap Disruption
  • Boardwipe
  • Revival

Reccommend Combo Guide (from Static1220):
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QfoBom37z8k

What do we want our deckmaster to do? Beargram, Shelled Emperor of the Forest Crown 

- Boardwipe
- Prevent monster effects in response to our Spells/Traps
- Self-reviving Beatstick

While Beargram, Shelled Emperor of the Forest Crown can be summoned from GY, we choose to have him as the Deckmaster for the convience of not having to search him out. This is a powerful boss - 3400 ATK alongside a powerful boardwipe makes him immediatly extrodinarly fearsome. Beargram, Shelled Emperor of the Forest Crown provides enormous support for our Traps, allowing them to be activated without fear of negation from our opponent's monsters. 

Boardwipe

- Clear Threats!
- Our Traptrix link monsters are unaffected by our own Trap Boardwipes! 

We aim to boardwipe, but not lose our own monsters! A way to do this is by having only Traptrix on board, which are unaffected by trap boardwipes, or having only Insect/Plants and using the boardwipe our Deckmaster has (Beargram, Shelled Emperor of the Forest Crown). This transforms what should have been a symetrical effect into one that activly benefits us!

Trap Disruption

- Clear Threats!
- Constant stream of threats due to Traptrix Cularia and Traptrix Sera 

Our main access of traps is through Traptrix Sera, easily setting Trap Hole traps when we activate Traptrix monster effects. This constant stream of traps will ensure we can control the board to become non-threatening.
Trap Hole traps for Traptrix Sera and Traptrix Rafflesia: 

  • Bottomless Trap Hole 
  • Floodgate Trap Hole (great for restricting other deckmasters)
  • Traptrix Holeutea (combo piece)
  • Void Trap Hole 
  • Traptrix Trap Hole Nightmare 
  • Gravedigger's Trap Hole 

Outside of Trap Holes, we utilize recursive traps like Titanocider , Ragnaraika Wisteria of Woe , and Lost Wind. Other traps may be accessed using Trap Tracks or Sales Pitch  

Revival

- Use Vernusylph to Return our monsters to the battlefield!
- Low cost to revive Ragnaraika!  
- Grind them down!

While we only have single copies of every card, our revivals allow us to use them again and again. We make use of this concept in our choice of side engines Ragnaraika which has a built in revival, and our deckmaster Beargram, Shelled Emperor of the Forest Crown which also has a built in revival. Naturia Camellia also provides an easy way to revive Naturia monsters
In particular, with Vernusylph, Traptrip Garden and Traptrix Holeutea we wish to revive Traptrix Sera since she provides so much value with both her effects every turn we trigger them. 
Eventually, our opponents will run out of resources
Good Revival targets: 

  • Traptrix Sera 
  • Ragnaraika Stag Sovereign 
  • Traptrix Myrmeleo 
  • Sacred Tree Beast, Hyperyton 
  • Beargram, Shelled Emperor of the Forest Crown 
  • Redox, Dragon Ruler of Boulders 
  • Naturia Camellia 

Revial methods: 

  • Vernusylph / Redox, Dragon Ruler of Boulders 
  • Traptrip Garden (for Traptrix monsters)
  • Traptrix Holeutea (for Traptrix monsters)
  • Naturia Camellia (for Naturia monsters)
  •  Ragnaraika / Beargram (self)

Other Considerations:

Spells: Trap Gatherer 

Traps: Chain Hole , Paleozoic Marrella 

Monsters: Alpha, the Master of Beasts , Beetrooper Assault Roller , Aztekipede, the Worm Warrior 

One Step Closer, One Step Too Late.

deck_excerpt: Dracoslayer, SHS Majespecter with a Performage Engine
deck_description:
The deck is a lot of gas but also kind of convoluted (Pendulum decks in a nutshell lol) and all credit goes to Usman Mannan on Youtube

Though it can easily turn just Wakaushi and Fire Dancer into a V-Link with Singularity (3 bounces), Exceed and Seals while also having Tri-Gate co-linked to Exceed, Singularity and Earlie AS WELL as Bagooska because why not?

Odd-Eyes Revolution Dragon being able to revive Ignister Prominence, the Blasting Dracoslayer with its Pendulum effect that is NOT ONCE PER TURN is insane recursion that just keeps churning more and more bodies out to keep the linking going. The main combo uses Ignister's "summon from deck" effect at least 5-6 times

Extra Deck is a bit tight but this list (courtesy of Thomas Wayne on youtube, his video is linked) is pretty much the best you can accomplish with a pure Performage build. There's sadly not a lot of interruption to deal with going second but the deck can still do some fun plays anyway. I wouldn't pull it out at a high level tournament though lol. Last 3 spots in Side go to Mulcharmy Purulia but I didn't want to put her into the list because the Charmies always inflate the shown price too much and you can also just opt for something more budget.
A Performage deck that is more competitive in its endboard (as long as you don't get interrupted).

deck_description: Another Performage deck list, this time keeping it well under 30 euros :D

Here are a few options, playing with different angles of intrigue: Option 1 (Focus on Chaos and Duality): "Angels and demons clash in a symphony of light and shadow! This deck weaves the forbidden power of Darklords with the radiant might of Lightsworns, a volatile fusion capable of unleashing devastating combos. Witness the rise of Morningstar, the descent of Judgment Dragon, and the chaotic dance of fate as we navigate the graveyard's depths. Will you embrace the divine or succumb to the infernal? The choice is a coin flip... with a loaded die." Option 2 (Focus on Graveyard Manipulation and OTK Potential): "The graveyard is our canvas, and milling is our masterpiece! This deck thrives on sending key pieces to the abyss, fueling explosive plays with Darklord Contact and Solar Recharge. From the celestial heights of Minerva to the infernal depths of Darklord Rebellion, we manipulate the fallen to unleash a devastating barrage of monsters, culminating in a swift and merciless OTK. Prepare to be buried under the weight of our graveyard's might!" Option 3 (Focus on Unexpected Power and Variety): "A motley crew of fallen angels, radiant knights, and cosmic horrors assemble! This deck defies categorization, blending Darklord control with Lightsworn aggression and a sprinkle of Extra Deck surprises. From the unpredictable might of Draglubion to the devastating power of Numeron Dragon, we wield a diverse arsenal to overwhelm any opponent. Expect the unexpected, and prepare for a chaotic symphony of power that will leave you speechless." Option 4 (Focus on the Darklord Theme with a Lightsworn Twist): "The Darklords have returned, but they've brought unexpected allies from the heavens. This deck twists the classic Darklord strategy with the relentless milling power of Lightsworns, creating a hybrid threat that overwhelms opponents with both control and aggression. Banishment of the Darklords and Darklord Contact ensure our fallen angels rise again and again, while the Lightsworn engine fuels our Extra Deck's devastating finishers. Prepare to witness a dark ascension unlike any other."

deck_excerpt: Ancient Gear has finally recieved their final piece of support in the real life Yugioh TCG - and that is Ancient Gear Statue!
deck_description:
My FAVOURITE archetype of ALL TIME Ancient Gear has finally recieved their final piece of support in the real life Yugioh TCG - and that is Ancient Gear Statue!
 
Ancient Gear Statue, Ancient Gear Dark Golem, Ancient Gear Advance, Ancient Gear Commander, Ancient Gear Tanker and Ancient Gear Duel all make it much easier to generate an entire army of Ancient Gear juggernauts to obliterate all your opponent's board and lifepoints - even in a metagame dominated by Ryzeal, Maliss and Blue-Eyes! 
 
There is now a heavy emphasis on Dr. Crowler's ace monster, Ancient Gear Golem, and now we're actually incentivized to summon it a lot and make fusion boss monsters like Ultimate Ancient Gear Golem and Megaton Golem! Let's blind second and teach these lame SLIFER RED duelists what the true meaning of having a PhD in dueling, just like our beloved Dr. Vellian Crowler! Time to blind second and MECHANIZED MELEE!!!
 
The deck is on the bigger side consisting of 47 cards instead of being 40 sharp. This is to make sure that you statistically draw your bricks/garnets less often, and that you can draw more starters/staples. The big size of 47 cards is possible due to the additional 3 starters we received in Maze of the Master, granting Ancient Gear a grand total of 15 one-card starters (Statue, Advance, Wyvern, Frame and Urgent Schedule), so you still have a big chance of drawing into your plays! 

If you want a thorough guide on this deck, check out my article from last year.
 
The following games are just my practice matches before I bring the deck to Locals in a honest attempt to top with my favourite deck of all time. 
 
Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!
 
GLHF Duelists!

deck_excerpt: Bistro Butcher Mill OTK ft. Critias
deck_description:
Greetings! Have you ever wondered how to mill your opponent with Bistro consistently? If you are, this deck does wonders. So, let's give it a shot!

 

 

Gameplan

1) During the game, do the followings:

  • Play Burning >>> Broken and activate Burning to skip your opponent's Main Phase 1 later on.
  • Place Stardust to where Saryuja would point to.
  • Activate Black Garden + Chain Summoning + Into the Void.

2) Replace Stardust with Critias via "Legend of Heart" to where would Saryuja point to, which would let you play "Chain Summoning" thanks to Saryuja and Garden being activated by force. Then, bring forth these monsters in this order below:

  • First, Special Summon Bistro with Saryuja away from where Bistro would be pointed by Saryuja.
  • Next, Tribute Summon Patrician by tributing Saryuja.
  • Finally, Normal Summon Wanghu.

3) With lots of flowers planted to opposing side, gift Wanghu to the opponent with "Mystic Box". If you have Shark + Wattfox in your hand and played Void beforehand, set all Traps and end your turn.

4) When it's Draw Phase of your opponent, with Shark + Wattfox in your GY, activate Front to target Wattfox and activate Yang, in whichever order you like. What matters the most is that by destroying Wattfox with Wanghu, your opponent can't really do anything.

5) Since you have skipped your opponent's Main Phase 1 with Burning >>> Broken, that leaves your opponent to be stuck into Battle Phase thanks to "Yang Zing Unleashed". Your opponent has to attack with Wanghu and flowers but there is a catch: You can actually choose which monster they would tackle thanks to Patrician. There are two ways you can go with...

  • When your opponent has one monster, direct into Critias to activate Critias and set Front to trigger it. Target Shark to revive, which lets you plant again with Garden.
  • When your opponent's side is full, direct into Bistro to mill your opponent. Keep going until you win the game!

 

If you wonder how to save up some SR and UR points, I can show you:

- "Pot of Avarice" can be collected by purchasing "Re-Contract Universe" deck. 90 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

- "Wonder Wand" and "Spellbook of Knowledge" can be collected by purchasing "Spellbook of Prophecy" deck. 120 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

- "Back to the Front" can be collected by purchasing "Rage of Cipher" deck. 30 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

- "Black Garden" can be found within "Exquisite Jet-Black Rose" Secret Pack to save 30 SR!

- "Number 60: Dugares the Timeless" can be found within "Number Recall" Secret Pack to save 30 SR!

- "Into The Void" + "Allure of Darkness" can be found within "The Infinite Void" Secret Pack to save 180 SR!

- "Moray of Avarice" can be found within "Treasures of the Cosmic Ocean" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

- "T.G. Hyper Librarian" can be found within "Futuristic Creatures" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

- "Pot of Acquistiveness" + "Ravenous" + "King Tiger Wanghu" + "Legendary Knight Critias" + "The Fang of Critias" can be found within "Legacy Pack" to save 150 SR!

- "Formula Synchron" + "Accel Synchro Stardust Dragon" can be found within "Evoked Dragon of Miracles" Secret Pack to save 60 SR and 30 UR!

 

So, in total, you can save up to 690 SR and 90 UR, if you are willing to spend some gems. Other SR and UR cards I didn't mention are essential.

 

That's all for this one. If you have any questions, feel free to ask. Have fun in Master Duel!

>Powers: Pops, return to hand, anti-hand traps, Omni negates, monster/spell/trap negates, bulk monster negates/return to hand/banish, infinite hand loops, immune to multiple pops, negates, hand traps,  even most of the floodgates.

>Card usages:

Deepsea king=4 level 4 = 2 frog (detaching mermails activate their effects, too)

Poseidra= return hand, send to gy

Megalo= send to gy+ negate /summon"equip spell"

Abysstus= send gy+ add

Ice jade= send gy + token synchro 

Eria= send gy+ search

Dragoon= search

Abyssspike= search, send

Abyssrhine= send, summon level 7 "usually the deepsea or poseidra"

Minstrel= use early in the duel to cut nibiru or any other hand trap/ send and summon

Squad= free summon when sent

Diva= free summon

Infantry= pop

Prince= send, search, summon

Atristan = summon

Moray= unbrick

Abyss/Mermail equip = negate/shuffle

Virtue= bulk pop

Elemental lord: hand rip

Statue: 🗿 

 

 

Read what the other extra deck monsters do

 

 

 

 

 

 

Little combo to consider

Diva, prince, send dragoon, get minstrel and abyssrhine

Cut any hand trap with minstrel, use abyssrhine to get deepsea and get 2 toads

Get link 3 neptabyss at some stage as he can auto equip a negate, either your turn or your opponent's 

 

 

Abyssrhine can send and draw a card from hand during your opponent, use it with infantry.

You can add infantry by frog from gy

 

 

Locked by droll? Focus on special summoning.

 

Maliss? Lancea 

Negates? You have lots of extenders

Blue eyes? Dweller

Rhyzeal? Let them pop you, they'll need like 20 :P

Only thing that would actually be a problem is a dimension shifter, usually called by grave or designator would do the job.

 

Also you can return kaiju to hand and resummon, yummy

 

 

Usually a first turn win without dimension shifter

deck_excerpt: An Egyptian pile deck for Domain that centers around the archetypes of Ishizu, Odion, and Marik with Pharaonic Advent as Deck Master
deck_description:
Ishtar Clan [ Odion(Temple of the Kings), Ishizu(Exchange of the Spirit), Marik, Gravekeepers, Egyptian Gods ]

Deckmaster: Pharaonic Advent

Domain: DARK, Spellcaster, Fairy, Fiend, Reptile 

Domain Discord Server

 

For some time, I wanted to make a Domain deck using the cards of the Ishtar Family, with *Pharaonic Advent* as the deckmaster. It is clear based on its effects that these archetypes were meant to work together. I am aware based on the current rules, Advent cannot use its effect to summon itself since it is an activated effect, and there is perhaps a more seamless deckmaster that just uses EARTH, but I want to commit to Advent, and he can still be tribute summoned.

I wanted to wait for the reveal of the Odion cards as well. Now that it has happened, I simply threw together the cards of Odion, Ishizu, Marik, Gravekeeper’s, Egyptian Gods Ra and Obelisk, as well as cool tech cards I like. I will admit, I quickly realized how cramped this deck would be, and I will have to go back and prune a bit if I want to make it more consistent and fit more staples. But I think this deck can still be fun and has interesting ideas. It will be a great foundation for me and others to build off from.

 

Odion and Ishizu (Temple of the Kings/Exchange of the Spirit)

The retrains of Odion and Ishizu have clear synergy, as we can get many cards into the graveyard and start up our engine, for example, using the of *Treasures of the King* by having a trap in our graveyard. *Gravekeeper’s Trap* can search for *Merciless Scorpion of Serket* as it’s an EARTH Fairy, and if we have *Temple of the Kings* in play, we can search for *Treasures of the Kings*, and Vice versa. If we already have our Odion engine up, we can instead get the OG Serket, then cheat out monsters from the Main Deck, or a Fusion from the Extra Deck. *Temple of the Kings* also allows us to activate a trap the turn it was set, which can really help with our suite of trap monsters and techs.

The two archetypes come with many ways to control the board. The Odion cards working together will be able to negate and pop cards on the field, most notably *Apophis the Swamp Deity*. There will be plenty of chances to use *Defense of the Temple* to Superpoly an opponent’s monster away, and then we can fetch *Dangers of the Divine* to bring out Ra from banishment and non-destruct wipe the entire board. I would also love to resolve *Exchange of Despair and Hope* in a domain game, which can either be powerful if *Exchange of the Spirit* is in grave, or incredibly funny to have all players summon monsters from each other’s graveyards.

Another form of control is good ol’ handripping! With that long-forgotten Ishizu card *Zolga the Prophet*, we can take a peek at our opponent’s deck and use *Gravekeeper’s Trap* to have them toss their card draw. But that can only do so much in a Domain game, and we can do better. I threw in *Convulsion of Nature*, so that all players must play with their deck flipped upside down, allowing the top card of the deck to be seen. So, all we need to do is ask what card is on top of our opponent’s deck and simply resolve the effect to discard. Your opponents will love you!

 

Marik (Egyptian Gods and Gravekeeper’s)

Looking at the deck list, you can tell there are not too many cards specific to Marik in the deck, as most of them are not great and do not mesh with his siblings, as well as cards falling out of domain (A lot of WATER/Aqua monsters). But we are committed to the bit, and we can run fiends. So we have *Lava Golem* which is a solid removal tool in general, and *Makyura the Destructor* does help us get a vital trap activated from the hand. I imagine there is some great fiend support we can run to get bodies on board for summoning Advent and tributing to fetch a Continuous trap.

*Winged Dragon of Ra* is also a Marik card, and you better believe we’re running Ra cards. *Winged Dragon of Ra – Sphere Mode* is excellent removal, especially in Domain as it can be used on the 3rd or 4rth player in rotation from you and they won’t be able to link it away, meaning it will come back to you after your next opponent’s turn. Ra also works with Odion’s deck, as mentioned before, we can turbo it with *Danger’s of the Divine* and then it will come back to our hand.

*Obelisk the Tormentor* and his support cards work very well with Ishizu, as we can mill *Soul Energy Max* to get Obelisk to our hand, then immediately summon it if we have the tributes on field. This could be an excellent combo with *Exchange of Despair and Hope*, for if our opponent has 3 monsters on field, we can summon 3 and then tribute them for Obelisk. We can also combo *The True Name* with *Convulsion of Nature* or *Zolga the Prophet* to get an extra draw and summon Obelisk. We could run Slifer as well, but for now the deck is already crowded as it is, and Ra and Obelisk are more thematic.

So, why are Gravekeeper’s here? Well, they are one my long-time favorite archetypes, they represent the Ishtar family as they are protectors of the Pharaoh’s tomb, and they were even part of Marik’s structure deck that released some time ago. But do they work with the deck? *Necrovalley* is critical to the archetype, but can lock down our graveyard, which can inhibit our plays. This is where the Field Spell techs come in. *Cosmo Queen the Queen of Prayers* is a card I have been excited about for some time. She allows us to switch out *Treasures of the Kings* into *Necrovalley* after our plays are done to inhibit our opponents. *Gravekeeper’s Trap* can also search for Gravekeeper’s monsters in addition to EARTH Fairies. We can get Gravekeeper’s Chief to open up our GY while still locking down our opponents. 

Here’s to hoping we get Marik’s retrain deck soon!

 

Themes and Tech Cards

[Field Spell Engine] – As mentioned with Gravekeeper’s, with cards like Cosmo Queen, *Multi-Universe*, and *Krishnerd Witch*, we can cycle through and protect our field spells. *Terraforming* and *Metaverse* will fetch our field spells from the deck. *Krishnerd Witch* in particular can work great with *Treasures of the Kings*. Once the spell’s effect is activated, Krishnerd can summon any monster that mentions *Temple of the Kings* from the GY or BZ, as the field spell’s name is treated as such while face up. Cosmo Queen can destroy our field spell and we’ll get a new one from our deck with a different name. For example, we can destroy *Necrovalley* and then search for Treasures. If we already used Treasures however, we can shuffle it back into our deck with *D.D. Post*. This way we are able to recycle it and use it’s activation effect to set an Apophis trap repeatedly. Cosmo Queen can also negate an opponents field spell and search any from our deck, which is sure to occur often in a domain game. I also threw in *Land Flipping* as a funny way to swap field spells. You can give them *Necrovalley* and still use *Treasures of the Kings*.

[Tribute Summoning] – Between the Egyptian Gods, *Pharaonic Advent* and our Gravekeepers, there quite a bit of Tribute summoning occurring in our deck. Luckily there is *Ultimate Offering* and *Ultimeat Offering*, which allow us to summon many times during our main phase as well as our opponent’s battle phase, which will come up quite often in a domain game. This actually combos well with *Makyura the Destructor* as we can summon him, then tribute him to summon a level 6 so that we may activate a trap from our hand. More tribute support like *The Monarchs Stormforth* might also be considered.

[Trap Monsters] – There are a plethora of trap monsters that we can run. We of course have the Apophis monsters for our Odion engine. The Tiki monsters, *Angel Statue – Azurune*, *Statue of Anguish Pattern*, and *Kuekibo* act as great disruption and protection. We are further protected by *Imperial Custom* from battle and card effect destruction. Trap monsters are either very vulnerable or very tough, as they can be destroyed by Spell/Trap and Monster removal. But at the same, a card like *Imperial Custom* will protect them from both Spell/Trap and Monster destruction. So *Dark Hole* will not destroy your trap monsters when *Imperial Custom* is on the field. *You’re Finished* seems like an excellent card for domain, as mid/late game will have many effects activating. *That’s 10!* is a perfect card for our domain deck, as it will build up many counters and allow us to set a Trap Monster from deck that can activate that turn! And it can be reset over and over again! A cool fact with trap monsters, when they are used as material or an XYZ summon, they are treated as trap cards, so going into *Time Thief Redoer* with a Level 4 trap monster will give him an instant bounce. *Booby Trap E* and *Boogie Trap* are great for getting our traps from grave, and of course, our deckmaster *Pharaonic Advent* can search all of these.

[*Shapesister*] – A cool Trap Monster that is also a Tuner, thus we have Synchros with our level 4’s. We can search for Krishnerd with Rciela, flip the field with Silvera, Take control of a monster with *Mind Castlin, or Fusion summon with *Muddy Mudragon*.

[*D.D. Post*] - an excellent card for recycling our resources. We can shuffle back anything from our hand, grave, or banishment. We can get our millers back in the deck and retrieve them with *Gravekeeper’s Trap*, our Odion cards and retrieve them with Treasures and *The Man with the Mask*, and even our *Winged Dragon of Ra*, which means we can cycle through our Sphere and Phoenix modes easily.

[*Metamorphosis*] - This card gives us a number of options from our Extra Deck. We can go into *Elder Entity Norden* to then summon that same monster we tributed, giving us two bodies on board for a tribute or XYZ summon. *Dark Magician the Dragon Knight* can protect our spells and traps from card destruction, and *Gravekeeper’s Supernaturalist* can protect our *Necrovalley* and search for other Gravekeeper’s Cards. I thought about adding a Dark Magician Package, that centered around Dragon Knight, *Eternal Soul*, and *Magician’s Combination*. With DM, DMG, and Palladium Oracles Mahad and Mana, there would be some more spellcasters and a little bit more of that Ancient Egyptian flavor. It’s just one of the many routes I can take with this deck.

[*Summer Schoolwork Successful!*] - Now this card I just had to fit in the deck. While it’s not likely that the win condition can be resolved, many players in a Domain game will be running cards like *Painful Choice*, *Slash Draw*, *Burial*, and other cards that send from deck to grave. 4000 is a lot of LP too, and it can reset itself from the grave! And since it is a continuous Trap, it can be search by Advent.

 

Conclusion

As one might tell from this deck, my favorite Yu-Gi-Oh show was Duel Monsters, and my favorite arch by far was Battle City. I loved the characters, the epic Egyptian God Cards, and I’ve always been heavily drawn to the Ancient Egyptian aesthetic and backstory of the Yu-Gi-Oh franchise. So I hope this deck gets even more support and gets better over time. There are so many directions to take this deck, and so many more archetypes to try and swap in and out. I’m just a novice when it comes to deck building, so I’ll be sure to explore even more possibilities. Domain in particular is great for this kind of deck because you can throw all these themes together and still have fun, even if they don’t perfectly combine. Thanks for your time, and I hope this list will help you.

KanaanBaal

مجموعة بطاقات "Gimmick Puppet" في لعبة "Yu-Gi-Oh!" هي مجموعة وحوش من نوع الآلة ذات سمة الظلام، وتشتهر بقدرتها على استدعاء وحوش Xyz من الرتبة 4 و8. إليك وصف تفصيلي لهذه المجموعة:

أسلوب اللعب:

  • التركيز على وحوش Xyz: تعتمد المجموعة بشكل أساسي على استدعاء وحوش Xyz القوية، وخاصةً وحوش الرتبة 8 مثل "Number 15: Gimmick Puppet Giant Grinder" و"Number C15: Gimmick Puppet Serial Killer".
  • التدمير والتأثيرات القوية: تتميز وحوش Xyz في هذه المجموعة بتأثيرات مدمرة، مثل تدمير وحوش الخصم أو إلحاق أضرار كبيرة بنقاط حياته.
  • الاستدعاء المتكرر: تتمتع بعض وحوش "Gimmick Puppet" بقدرات تسمح باستدعائها بشكل متكرر من المقبرة، مما يسهل استدعاء وحوش Xyz.

أهم البطاقات:

  • Gimmick Puppet Dreary Doll: بطاقة أساسية تسمح باستدعاء وحوش "Gimmick Puppet" من المقبرة.
  • Gimmick Puppet Magnet Doll: بطاقة تساعد في استدعاء وحوش Xyz من خلال تغيير مستويات الوحوش في الملعب.
  • Number 15: Gimmick Puppet Giant Grinder: وحش Xyz قوي يمكنه تدمير وحوش الخصم وإلحاق أضرار كبيرة.
  • Number C15: Gimmick Puppet Serial Killer: نسخة أقوى من "Giant Grinder" بتأثيرات مدمرة إضافية.

نقاط القوة:

  • قدرة عالية على استدعاء وحوش Xyz القوية.
  • تأثيرات مدمرة تتيح التحكم في الملعب.

نقاط الضعف:

مجموعة "Gimmick Puppet" هي خيار جيد للاعبين الذين يفضلون أسلوب اللعب الذي يعتمد على وحوش Xyz القوية والتأثيرات المدمرة. تتطلب المجموعة بعض الممارسة لإتقانها، ولكنها يمكن أن تكون فعالة للغاية في المباريات.

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

The "Gimmick Puppet" card deck in "Yu-Gi-Oh!" is a dark themed machine-type monster set, famous for its ability to summon rank 4 and 8 XYZ monsters. Here is a detailed description of this group:

Gameplay:

Focus on XYZ monsters: The collection is mainly based on summoning powerful Xyz monsters, especially rank 8 monsters such as "Number 15: Gimmick Puppet Giant Grinder" and "Number C15: Gimmick Puppet Serial Killer".
Destruction and powerful effects: The Xyz monsters in this group feature devastating effects, such as destroying opponent monsters or inflicting significant damage on his life points.
Frequent summoning: Some "Gimmick Puppet" monsters have abilities that allow them to be repeatedly summoned from the cemetery, making it easier to summon XYZ monsters.

The most important cards:

Gimmick Puppet Dreary Doll: A base card that allows summoning "Gimmick Puppet" monsters from the cemetery.
Gimmick Puppet Magnet Doll: A card that helps summon XYZ monsters by changing monster levels on the field.
Number 15: Gimmick Puppet Giant Grinder: A powerful Xyz monster that can destroy opponent monsters and inflict significant damage.
Number C15: Gimmick Puppet Serial Killer: A more powerful version of "Giant Grinder" with additional devastating effects.

Strengths:

High ability to summon powerful XYZ monsters.
Destructive effects allow the stadium to be controlled.
The possibility of repeated recall gives the group flexibility in playing.

Vulnerabilities:

The collection may be slow at first and need time to prepare the playground.
It relies heavily on XYZ monsters, making them vulnerable to cards that disrupt your summons.

In general:

The "Gimmick Puppet" collection is a good option for players who prefer a gameplay based on powerful Xyz monsters and devastating effects. The group requires some practice to master, but it can be very effective in matches.

deck_description: blue eyes primite feat dragon master magia

Here are a few deck description options, aiming for "interesting" in different ways:

Option 1 (Focus on Chaotic Synergy):

"A blooming nightmare! This deck is a botanical blender, throwing Rikka's frosty precision, Aromage's fragrant healing, and Predaplant's venomous chaos into a pot, then stirring with Generaider might. Expect unpredictable plays, fusion frenzy, and enough plant-based shenanigans to make a botanist weep...or join the madness. Prepare for a garden party where every flower has teeth!"

Option 2 (Focus on Resource Management & Grind):

"They say 'stop and smell the roses,' but this deck grinds your opponent into fertilizer. We're cultivating a garden of advantage, using Rikka's control, Aromage's life point manipulation, and Pot of Desires to fuel an endless cycle of disruption and recursion. From the snow-covered petals of Rikka to the fragrant winds of Aroma, every card is a resource, and every turn is a step towards inevitable bloom...and your opponent's demise."

Option 3 (Focus on Unexpected Combos & Fusion):

"Fusion? Plants? Life points? YES! This deck is a chaotic symphony of disparate strategies, harmonized by the power of Super Polymerization and Instant Fusion. Witness the birth of Starving Venom from the most unlikely of ingredients, or watch as Rikka and Aroma unite to summon devastating Extra Deck threats. From the delicate Rikka Queen to the ferocious Predaplant Ambulomelides, prepare for a floral fusion fiesta that defies all expectations."

Option 4 (Focus on Flavor & Story):

"In a world where winter meets spring, a fragile alliance blossoms. The icy Rikka, seeking to protect their frozen domain, join forces with the life-giving Aromage, desperate to heal a world choked by shadow. But lurking in the depths of their garden are the predatory Predaplants, their venomous tendrils ready to corrupt. This deck tells a story of fragile cooperation and hidden dangers, where every card is a petal in a tale of survival and growth."

Option 5 (Short, Punchy, and Intriguing):

"Rikka? Aroma? Predaplant? Yes. All of them. And it's a beautiful, terrifying mess. Prepare to be flowered."

deck_name: Team APS Dark Magician Structure Deck 2025
deck_description: Deck built from Team APS video (BLUE-EYES vs DARK MAGICIAN) 2025

The White Forest version of Blue eyes ! A great version still very much unexplored by competitive players, The white forest cards can search the Blue Eyes ones (And Also Veiler), also synergizing fantasticly thanks to the generic requirements of the Blue Eyes Link 1.

This deck also really never runs out of gas with a decent Hand, so it can survive various interruptions, and if it goes uninterrupted... Oh boy, the end board will be composed of a floodgate and more than 7 negates, so the opponent will have no chance to win.

Give this deck a chance ! This is my own personal version, but you can experiment so much with this version, it has so many possibilities !
Main Blue-Eyes deck for a more competitive feel

deck_excerpt: Spright Elf, Beatrice and Fiendsmith shouldn't be legal all at once... Oh well, time to use it in White Forest Azamina!
deck_description:
Spright Elf, Beatrice and Fiendsmith shouldn't be legal all at once... Oh well, time to use it in White Forest Azamina!

White Forest certainly has grown up and evolved with the various pieces of support given to the strategy over the months it has been around, and with the latest indirect support in Masterduel, White Forest has become completely unfair! Fiendsmith Engraver has become a 1-card combo for the strategy, being able to access Astellar of the White Forest via Beatrice and reviving it with Spright Elf!

Elzette Azamina simultaneously bridges White Forest, Azamina and Sinful Spoils together into one cohesive deck since she summons herself essentially for free and can search any Sinful Spoils card when she's used as synchro material! Sinful Spoils of the White Forest also has recently been released as well, allowing White Forest to fusion summon its fusion monsters Ilia Silvia or more notably, Guardian Chimera! The extra consistency that this deck has now allows White Forest to not only use the sizeable Toy Box engine and Bystial package, it allows room for a whopping 19 staple cards! 
 
Increased consistency, enhanced power level and additional extension for White Forest makes the deck an incredible contender for March 2025's Duelist Cup!

If you want a thorough guide on how to play this deck, check out my earlier article!

 
Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!
